00:00:25.630 --> 00:00:32.850
PROFESSOR: So where we left it
last time is the access to

00:00:32.850 --> 00:00:35.860
family planning, the access to
contraception, et cetera, did

00:00:35.860 --> 00:00:40.200
not play such an important
role in keeping people's

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:41.110
families small.

00:00:41.110 --> 00:00:43.130
It doesn't mean that it's
not a good thing to do.

00:00:43.130 --> 00:00:45.295
It certainly helps people
time their fertility.

00:00:45.295 --> 00:00:49.270
It makes them happier and all
other good things, but it was

00:00:49.270 --> 00:00:52.880
not the main determinant
of family size.

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:56.280
And so then the next question,
obviously, is then what is the

00:00:56.280 --> 00:00:58.530
determinant of family size?

00:00:58.530 --> 00:01:02.790
If people are not constrained
by their lack of access to

00:01:02.790 --> 00:01:05.010
contraception to choose the
family size that they want,

00:01:05.010 --> 00:01:08.670
how do they decide to choose
their family size?

00:01:08.670 --> 00:01:14.610
And there are, I think, only
two big classes of factors

00:01:14.610 --> 00:01:16.140
that might matter.

00:01:16.140 --> 00:01:22.280
One is social factors, so both
what the community thinks is

00:01:22.280 --> 00:01:25.010
right, what the country thinks
is right, what your husband

00:01:25.010 --> 00:01:26.810
thinks is right.

00:01:26.810 --> 00:01:33.550
And the other is the cost and
benefits of having sex, which

00:01:33.550 --> 00:01:37.300
is pleasant, and having babies,
which you might or

00:01:37.300 --> 00:01:40.620
might not want to have at a
specific time of your life.

00:01:40.620 --> 00:01:44.420
So both of these things are
traded off in some ways.

00:01:44.420 --> 00:01:47.310
And the issue is whether people
do that effectively,

00:01:47.310 --> 00:01:53.040
whether they do that
voluntarily, whether there is

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:54.990
some correction coming
from society or

00:01:54.990 --> 00:01:56.600
something like that.

00:01:56.600 --> 00:02:00.270
So social norms clearly
play a role.

00:02:00.270 --> 00:02:03.190
So one example is this example
of Matlab, in Bangladesh,

00:02:03.190 --> 00:02:06.500
where this program was
introduced, and a community

00:02:06.500 --> 00:02:09.740
worker came and tried
to persuade woman.

00:02:09.740 --> 00:02:14.170
One thing that has happened is
that, at the beginning of the

00:02:14.170 --> 00:02:17.350
program, the introduction
was very, very slow.

00:02:17.350 --> 00:02:20.080
The take-up of contraception
was very, very slow.

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:24.180
And then it started to explode,
the take-up started

00:02:24.180 --> 00:02:25.340
to explode.

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:28.090
And then it comes down again.

00:02:28.090 --> 00:02:33.320
So you get a little bit of an
s-shape in adoption of the

00:02:33.320 --> 00:02:34.940
contraception.

00:02:34.940 --> 00:02:38.070
And what kind of mechanism would
explain, what kind of

00:02:38.070 --> 00:02:41.500
social mechanism explains this
kind of diffusion curve?

00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:43.960
You must have seen that, either
in other classes or you

00:02:43.960 --> 00:02:45.210
can think about it.

00:02:47.574 --> 00:02:48.470
AUDIENCE: Viruses.

00:02:48.470 --> 00:02:49.140
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:02:49.140 --> 00:02:52.030
This is how viruses spread.

00:02:52.030 --> 00:02:57.940
This is also how iPads spread
or any new innovation.

00:02:57.940 --> 00:03:01.600
And why does it spread
in this way?

00:03:01.600 --> 00:03:04.301
Why does it have this shape?

00:03:04.301 --> 00:03:07.780
AUDIENCE: If it's contagious,
initially, then a smaller

00:03:07.780 --> 00:03:10.265
group of people haven't.

00:03:10.265 --> 00:03:12.583
I guess that people that
interact with each other at

00:03:12.583 --> 00:03:13.744
some point.

00:03:13.744 --> 00:03:16.974
I mean it kind of depends
on something, I

00:03:16.974 --> 00:03:18.217
don't exactly know.

00:03:18.217 --> 00:03:20.720
I don't know the exact
mechanism.

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:21.215
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:03:21.215 --> 00:03:25.040
But you get the drift.

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:30.130
It spreads mostly like viruses
or new products, which spread

00:03:30.130 --> 00:03:32.555
mostly by infection.

00:03:35.090 --> 00:03:38.910
At the beginning, no one is
infected, so the innovation or

00:03:38.910 --> 00:03:40.800
the virus doesn't spread.

00:03:40.800 --> 00:03:42.580
And then more and more
people get infected.

00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:44.810
So they get chances to
infect more people.

00:03:44.810 --> 00:03:47.090
So there is a sudden take off.

00:03:47.090 --> 00:03:49.950
And then after a while,
everybody is infected.

00:03:49.950 --> 00:03:52.910
So the infection has nowhere
to go anymore.

00:03:52.910 --> 00:03:56.530
So that's why we find this kind
of mechanism, both for

00:03:56.530 --> 00:03:58.440
viruses and for new things.

00:04:02.665 --> 00:04:07.200
So the fact that in Matlab the
contraception had the same

00:04:07.200 --> 00:04:11.430
spread, at first very slow and
then a sudden take off and

00:04:11.430 --> 00:04:14.610
then flattening out again, when
the take-up was larger,

00:04:14.610 --> 00:04:21.680
suggests there may have been a
contagion phenomenon going on.

00:04:21.680 --> 00:04:26.490
So to look at it more directly,
there's a paper by

00:04:26.490 --> 00:04:33.360
Kaivan Munshi, who looked at
what happened, whether people

00:04:33.360 --> 00:04:37.050
do the same thing that
their neighbors do.

00:04:37.050 --> 00:04:41.590
And so the first thing you can
do is to say, well, if there

00:04:41.590 --> 00:04:45.350
are 20 women in my neighborhood
and 19 have

00:04:45.350 --> 00:04:48.980
adopted the contraception, am I
more likely to adopt then if

00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:51.270
there is 0 who have adopted?

00:04:51.270 --> 00:04:53.730
And when you do that, you find
that indeed people, who had

00:04:53.730 --> 00:04:56.090
more people who adopted
around them, were also

00:04:56.090 --> 00:04:57.690
more likely to adopt.

00:04:57.690 --> 00:05:01.670
So is that necessarily a sign
that they're learning from

00:05:01.670 --> 00:05:02.340
each other?

00:05:02.340 --> 00:05:05.775
What else could be going on?

00:05:05.775 --> 00:05:07.659
AUDIENCE: It could just
be a copycat effect.

00:05:07.659 --> 00:05:09.543
So it's not necessarily that
you're learning, but you're

00:05:09.543 --> 00:05:11.130
just doing as you see
someone else do.

00:05:11.130 --> 00:05:11.420
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:05:11.420 --> 00:05:13.600
So the learning could
in a broad sense.

00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:15.370
First, it doesn't have to
be learning something.

00:05:15.370 --> 00:05:17.310
It could just be pure imitation,
where you're trying

00:05:17.310 --> 00:05:21.500
to figure out what's the
fashionable thing to do.

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:22.610
So there is no learning
going on.

00:05:22.610 --> 00:05:25.190
That's right.

00:05:25.190 --> 00:05:27.410
So this is going to be difficult
to separate, but

00:05:27.410 --> 00:05:28.250
even beyond that?

00:05:28.250 --> 00:05:28.735
Yeah?

00:05:28.735 --> 00:05:30.917
AUDIENCE: I guess if more people
around you are doing

00:05:30.917 --> 00:05:33.585
it, there is greater
demand in the area.

00:05:33.585 --> 00:05:35.040
[INAUDIBLE]

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:37.480
supplies, but it's just
inaccessible.

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:37.560
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:40.330
So there might be this effect,
which is it might be that, in

00:05:40.330 --> 00:05:42.690
response to the first demand
from the people, there is an

00:05:42.690 --> 00:05:43.930
excess in supply.

00:05:43.930 --> 00:05:46.920
Or it could even be that it
turns out that the community

00:05:46.920 --> 00:05:54.800
health worker is better in
that particular village.

00:05:54.800 --> 00:05:58.060
And so, because she's better
and more energetic, she got

00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:00.860
your neighbors to adopt and,
also, yourself to adopt.

00:06:00.860 --> 00:06:04.940
And the fact that you adopt when
you neighbor adopts is

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:08.450
not a sign that there is a
causal effect of neighbor's

00:06:08.450 --> 00:06:11.340
adoption on your, which could
be coming from copycat or

00:06:11.340 --> 00:06:14.370
coming from learning, but just
that there is one common

00:06:14.370 --> 00:06:17.310
factor that leads them to adopt
and leads you to adopt.

00:06:17.310 --> 00:06:21.150
So what he does is that he does
something very ingenious.

00:06:21.150 --> 00:06:25.700
He exploits the fact that most
of these villages have Hindus

00:06:25.700 --> 00:06:27.140
and Muslims.

00:06:27.140 --> 00:06:30.350
And there is only one community
health worker for

00:06:30.350 --> 00:06:31.890
both communities.

00:06:31.890 --> 00:06:33.530
But Hindus don't speak
to Muslims--

00:06:33.530 --> 00:06:35.490
certainly not about
contraception.

00:06:35.490 --> 00:06:37.970
And Muslims don't
speak to Hindus.

00:06:37.970 --> 00:06:44.050
So now he's looking at, if it
was the certain hypothesis

00:06:44.050 --> 00:06:47.420
that the reason why our actions
are correlated is

00:06:47.420 --> 00:06:49.720
because of the community
health worker.

00:06:49.720 --> 00:06:56.450
Should I see that, if I'm a
Muslim woman, there is also a

00:06:56.450 --> 00:06:59.120
correlation between my adoption
and that of the Hindu

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:02.290
woman if it's due to the
community health worker.

00:07:07.100 --> 00:07:08.140
AUDIENCE: Can you restate
the question?

00:07:08.140 --> 00:07:10.640
PROFESSOR: So if it is due to
the community health worker,

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:13.160
should I see a relationship
between the adoption of the

00:07:13.160 --> 00:07:16.392
Muslim woman and the adoption
of Hindu woman?

00:07:16.392 --> 00:07:17.810
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:07:17.810 --> 00:07:18.390
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:07:18.390 --> 00:07:21.110
If it is due to the community
health worker, because she's

00:07:21.110 --> 00:07:25.340
serving both communities, we
should see this correlation.

00:07:25.340 --> 00:07:26.590
Sorry, one more came.

00:07:26.590 --> 00:07:28.112
Thank you.

00:07:28.112 --> 00:07:29.362
Good effort.

00:07:32.280 --> 00:07:36.100
But if it is due to the social
learning, should we see a

00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:38.670
relationship between the
adoption of the Hindu woman

00:07:38.670 --> 00:07:41.680
and adoption of the
Muslim woman?

00:07:41.680 --> 00:07:42.470
No.

00:07:42.470 --> 00:07:45.360
So if it's due to the people
learning from each other or

00:07:45.360 --> 00:07:48.060
even copying each other, they
can't copy the Muslims,

00:07:48.060 --> 00:07:50.530
because they never will ask
them if they are Hindu and

00:07:50.530 --> 00:07:51.460
vice versa.

00:07:51.460 --> 00:07:52.460
So he does that.

00:07:52.460 --> 00:07:55.860
And what he finds is that the
correlation is only within

00:07:55.860 --> 00:07:58.920
community, which is an
indication that, probably,

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:01.385
people are trying to figure
out what's the social norm

00:08:01.385 --> 00:08:05.370
around the social group or
are copying each other.

00:08:05.370 --> 00:08:07.580
And it's just not a joint
effect of the

00:08:07.580 --> 00:08:10.050
community health worker.

00:08:10.050 --> 00:08:13.220
Another way in which you would
peak at the social norm is by

00:08:13.220 --> 00:08:15.490
watching what's on TV.

00:08:15.490 --> 00:08:21.120
And there is a very nice paper
on the telenovelas in Brazil.

00:08:21.120 --> 00:08:28.640
So Brazil is a very Catholic
country and, until relatively

00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:33.820
recently, was not a very free
society, until about

00:08:33.820 --> 00:08:35.590
15, 20 years ago.

00:08:35.590 --> 00:08:38.390
And it was certainly not
particularly encouraging

00:08:38.390 --> 00:08:40.030
family planning.

00:08:40.030 --> 00:08:46.130
But the telenovelas, which are
like soap operas, became very,

00:08:46.130 --> 00:08:48.040
very popular.

00:08:48.040 --> 00:08:51.170
And they became very popular,
in part, because they were

00:08:51.170 --> 00:08:52.700
quite good.

00:08:52.700 --> 00:08:54.950
And the reason why they
were quite good--

00:08:54.950 --> 00:08:59.060
I'm told, because I'm yet to
watch one, my Portuguese being

00:08:59.060 --> 00:09:02.630
not quite up to crack--

00:09:02.630 --> 00:09:06.890
is that a lot of people who
would otherwise have been

00:09:06.890 --> 00:09:10.270
artists in other fields could
not really do it very easily

00:09:10.270 --> 00:09:13.230
in Brazil, so they all went
and did telenovelas.

00:09:13.230 --> 00:09:19.800
And they were aired on one
channel, called Rede Globo,

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:24.070
which was not available
everywhere at the beginning,

00:09:24.070 --> 00:09:26.330
which progressively spread.

00:09:26.330 --> 00:09:29.840
So what this article did is
that they looked at the

00:09:29.840 --> 00:09:35.160
diffusion of the Rede Globo all
over Brazil and compared

00:09:35.160 --> 00:09:38.510
the number of children that a
women had before and after the

00:09:38.510 --> 00:09:42.920
introduction of Rede Globo
in places where it got

00:09:42.920 --> 00:09:43.910
introduced.

00:09:43.910 --> 00:09:46.260
So exploiting, in that way, the
progressive introduction.

00:09:46.260 --> 00:09:48.670
Of course, the cities got
it first and then

00:09:48.670 --> 00:09:49.830
the more rural areas.

00:09:49.830 --> 00:09:51.930
So places that got it first, in

00:09:51.930 --> 00:09:53.230
general, had fewer children.

00:09:53.230 --> 00:09:56.770
But if we compare before and
after you get it, in places

00:09:56.770 --> 00:09:59.450
that get it and places that
don't, then we get a sense

00:09:59.450 --> 00:10:01.840
about what is the effect
of Rede Globo.

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:07.040
And what they found is that
the women, who were of

00:10:07.040 --> 00:10:10.320
reproductive age after Rede
Globo was introduced, had

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:13.700
fewer children in their lifetime
then the places that

00:10:13.700 --> 00:10:17.090
were in reproductive age
before Rede Globo came.

00:10:17.090 --> 00:10:20.230
And another thing that was kind
of cute, as a result of

00:10:20.230 --> 00:10:26.030
that, is that many of the kids
that were born in this area

00:10:26.030 --> 00:10:30.160
were born after the characters
of the telenovelas.

00:10:30.160 --> 00:10:30.907
Yeah?

00:10:30.907 --> 00:10:33.769
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:33.769 --> 00:10:38.000
these telenovelas, the main
characters have few children?

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:38.790
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:10:38.790 --> 00:10:39.215
Exactly.

00:10:39.215 --> 00:10:44.930
The reason why this happened is
that the telenovelas were

00:10:44.930 --> 00:10:49.520
promoting, not necessarily for
the sake of it, but the main

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:53.610
characters in the telenovelas
were people, some of them with

00:10:53.610 --> 00:10:57.720
0 children, if they had
children, with a small family.

00:10:57.720 --> 00:11:00.770
So they were promoting a model
of like a modern woman who had

00:11:00.770 --> 00:11:05.560
few children, which kind of
helped or contributed to

00:11:05.560 --> 00:11:06.710
slowly shift the norm.

00:11:06.710 --> 00:11:09.460
Yes, Brazil expertise.

00:11:09.460 --> 00:11:13.300
AUDIENCE: So it was is like
the main channel.

00:11:13.300 --> 00:11:15.200
Like if there is one that people
actually don't have to

00:11:15.200 --> 00:11:17.852
pay, necessarily, for it, you
just get it for free, if you

00:11:17.852 --> 00:11:23.350
just have a TV So part of the
access to that channel comes

00:11:23.350 --> 00:11:28.440
with some areas that are growing
into big cities,

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:30.722
becoming a little bit
more industrialized.

00:11:30.722 --> 00:11:33.870
So that could be another
thing, stuff like that.

00:11:33.870 --> 00:11:40.350
People are getting access to
the TV channel, that means

00:11:40.350 --> 00:11:43.388
that the country as a whole
is becoming more and more

00:11:43.388 --> 00:11:44.384
industrialized.

00:11:44.384 --> 00:11:49.613
And they are sort of adapting
how many kids they have to fit

00:11:49.613 --> 00:11:51.870
the model a little bit better.

00:11:51.870 --> 00:11:52.280
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:11:52.280 --> 00:11:54.110
AUDIENCE: So the actual cause
could be different.

00:11:54.110 --> 00:11:59.200
Maybe it's not just the fact
that they were watching TV,

00:11:59.200 --> 00:12:01.510
but the fact that they
gained access to it

00:12:01.510 --> 00:12:03.060
and what that implies.

00:12:03.060 --> 00:12:05.450
PROFESSOR: So what you are
saying is that TV came on the

00:12:05.450 --> 00:12:08.060
tail of other changes
in the same areas?

00:12:08.060 --> 00:12:09.310
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:12:12.402 --> 00:12:16.114
Some places becoming a
little bit more urban

00:12:16.114 --> 00:12:19.070
and how that's changed.

00:12:19.070 --> 00:12:19.370
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:12:19.370 --> 00:12:22.100
So that's a very good point,
which is always with this

00:12:22.100 --> 00:12:24.590
different and difference
kind of strategy.

00:12:24.590 --> 00:12:28.160
The always are worried
about that.

00:12:28.160 --> 00:12:31.040
At least we are not comparing
directly the city to the rural

00:12:31.040 --> 00:12:34.440
areas, but we are comparing the
rural areas as they are

00:12:34.440 --> 00:12:37.940
becoming industrial enough
or developed

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:39.590
enough to get the channel.

00:12:39.590 --> 00:12:43.600
Because, presumably, the channel
decided to come when

00:12:43.600 --> 00:12:45.770
there was enough people who
were rich enough to buy a

00:12:45.770 --> 00:12:46.580
television.

00:12:46.580 --> 00:12:50.700
And therefore, they may have
been looking, not only at the

00:12:50.700 --> 00:12:55.410
level of development of the
place, but how it was moving.

00:12:55.410 --> 00:12:58.840
And if that is the case, then
we could be picking part of

00:12:58.840 --> 00:12:59.830
those trends.

00:12:59.830 --> 00:13:03.380
So that is something where we
could never be completely

00:13:03.380 --> 00:13:05.520
sure, because we haven't
randomized.

00:13:05.520 --> 00:13:10.590
So those underlying trends,
we don't observe them.

00:13:10.590 --> 00:13:13.350
And so it's quite possible
that you are right.

00:13:13.350 --> 00:13:17.780
So these doubts remain.

00:13:17.780 --> 00:13:22.150
What the author does is try to
look at whether there are

00:13:22.150 --> 00:13:30.450
trends in fertility before, that
the fertility was already

00:13:30.450 --> 00:13:34.960
a little bit declining before
the channel came in.

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:38.000
Which we would probably observe,
if the stories you're

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:42.550
talking about is the one, which
is, as I see that the

00:13:42.550 --> 00:13:44.590
place is becoming more
industrialized, richer et

00:13:44.590 --> 00:13:48.710
cetera, I'm putting the TV
there, as the president of

00:13:48.710 --> 00:13:49.920
Rede Globo.

00:13:49.920 --> 00:13:51.400
And they don't see that.

00:13:51.400 --> 00:13:54.950
They see kind of shift in trend
around the introduction

00:13:54.950 --> 00:13:55.900
of the television.

00:13:55.900 --> 00:13:57.420
