progress happening.

00:15:10.540 --> 00:15:13.740
So these are all indications
that something, which is

00:15:13.740 --> 00:15:16.760
probably not particularly
surprising, is in something as

00:15:16.760 --> 00:15:19.160
fundamental and deep
as how many

00:15:19.160 --> 00:15:22.460
children you want to have.

00:15:22.460 --> 00:15:24.460
The social norms around you--

00:15:24.460 --> 00:15:27.500
these are very local, your
village, your community, your

00:15:27.500 --> 00:15:32.760
family, your mother-in-law,
or society as a whole, as

00:15:32.760 --> 00:15:36.470
reflected to you by TV--

00:15:36.470 --> 00:15:37.910
matter.

00:15:37.910 --> 00:15:44.690
But there are also just plain,
simple, cost-benefit

00:15:44.690 --> 00:15:49.490
calculations about do I want a
kid at this time, do I want to

00:15:49.490 --> 00:15:52.230
take the risk of a kid at this
time by having unprotected

00:15:52.230 --> 00:15:54.140
sex, et cetera, et cetera.

00:15:54.140 --> 00:15:58.100
And one thing that I want to
argue is that people are very

00:15:58.100 --> 00:16:01.290
good at making those
calculations.

00:16:01.290 --> 00:16:08.970
And in the sense the key group
to look at for a test case of

00:16:08.970 --> 00:16:11.200
this are adolescent girls.

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:14.500
Because in these countries and
elsewhere, we kind of suspect

00:16:14.500 --> 00:16:17.770
adolescent girls to be not
the best at making those

00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:20.560
calculations, necessarily,
which is why we see some

00:16:20.560 --> 00:16:22.510
teenage pregnancies.

00:16:22.510 --> 00:16:26.520
And so if they can calculate,
then it would mean that,

00:16:26.520 --> 00:16:28.330
presumably, people can
calculate them.

00:16:28.330 --> 00:16:31.440
Another reason why it's very
interesting to look at

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:35.030
adolescents, in particular, in
Africa, is not only teenage

00:16:35.030 --> 00:16:37.240
pregnancy, but teenage pregnancy
as a sign that

00:16:37.240 --> 00:16:43.420
you've had unprotected sex,
which puts you at risk for a

00:16:43.420 --> 00:16:47.920
STDs, sexually transmitted
diseases, in particular, HIV.

00:16:47.920 --> 00:16:52.620
So adolescents have been called
the window of hope in

00:16:52.620 --> 00:16:57.720
the fight against HIV, because
A, they are uninfected.

00:16:57.720 --> 00:17:01.660
And once you're infected with
HIV, you're infected.

00:17:01.660 --> 00:17:03.980
You can't disinfect the people,
so it's better to

00:17:03.980 --> 00:17:05.520
catch them early.

00:17:05.520 --> 00:17:07.560
Second--

00:17:07.560 --> 00:17:10.069
and that goes back to the point
that you made earlier

00:17:10.069 --> 00:17:11.319
about was there a lag--

00:17:13.980 --> 00:17:17.650
people's sexual preferences,
their habits, et cetera, have

00:17:17.650 --> 00:17:18.660
not yet been formed.

00:17:18.660 --> 00:17:24.619
And maybe it's right time to
catch them to influence their

00:17:24.619 --> 00:17:26.829
behavior early, and then they'll
keep those patterns

00:17:26.829 --> 00:17:28.720
for the rest of their life.

00:17:28.720 --> 00:17:32.770
So there is a lot of effort,
the world over, to develop

00:17:32.770 --> 00:17:45.410
programs to try to teach kids
to have a safer sex life.

00:17:45.410 --> 00:17:48.250
And UNICEF worked on a lot
of these programs.

00:17:48.250 --> 00:17:52.480
But unfortunately, in a lot of
countries, there is some

00:17:52.480 --> 00:17:56.920
pressure to have this program
being mainly concerned about

00:17:56.920 --> 00:17:59.280
abstinence and faithfulness.

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:02.890
So the strategy that is employed
in eastern South

00:18:02.890 --> 00:18:05.730
Africa is called ABCD.

00:18:05.730 --> 00:18:11.350
So the A is for abstain, B for
be faithful, C is for use a

00:18:11.350 --> 00:18:15.630
condom, and D is or you die.

00:18:15.630 --> 00:18:23.710
So that kind of encapsulates the
HIV prevention strategy.

00:18:23.710 --> 00:18:27.850
But in primary schools, and
primary school in Kenya goes

00:18:27.850 --> 00:18:30.310
till grade eight, and people
start school late

00:18:30.310 --> 00:18:31.520
and repeat a lot.

00:18:31.520 --> 00:18:35.103
So really, kids are like
16, 17, they're

00:18:35.103 --> 00:18:36.600
still in primary school.

00:18:36.600 --> 00:18:40.380
So think of primary
and junior high.

00:18:40.380 --> 00:18:43.035
There was a policy decision that
was made in Kenya, which

00:18:43.035 --> 00:18:46.140
is still a pretty religious
country, that condoms could

00:18:46.140 --> 00:18:48.750
not be discussed in school.

00:18:48.750 --> 00:18:53.740
So the ABCD program is really
an ABD program,

00:18:53.740 --> 00:18:55.060
abstain or be faithful.

00:18:55.060 --> 00:18:59.440
And, in fact, it's a program,
which is all day long, to

00:18:59.440 --> 00:19:02.910
scare kids away and to say, look
everybody's dangerous.

00:19:02.910 --> 00:19:04.750
HIV is everywhere.

00:19:04.750 --> 00:19:07.900
The most dangerous kid is the
kid you meet in a disco.

00:19:07.900 --> 00:19:09.110
I'm not making any of this up.

00:19:09.110 --> 00:19:13.160
I've read the little UNICEF
books, where you have this

00:19:13.160 --> 00:19:16.400
little cartoon of a girl going
to a disco and meeting this

00:19:16.400 --> 00:19:19.410
boy and having sex and
then getting HIV.

00:19:19.410 --> 00:19:25.060
So this is the type of thing
that they are trying to put

00:19:25.060 --> 00:19:27.970
into people's heads.

00:19:27.970 --> 00:19:34.140
So basically, the message
becomes, abstain until you are

00:19:34.140 --> 00:19:37.310
of age to get married and
then get married.

00:19:37.310 --> 00:19:38.960
Now the big danger with
that is that kids

00:19:38.960 --> 00:19:40.580
decide, well, fine.

00:19:40.580 --> 00:19:41.910
I don't want to die.

00:19:41.910 --> 00:19:43.450
But I don't want to abstain.

00:19:43.450 --> 00:19:45.490
So let me get married.

00:19:45.490 --> 00:19:49.670
And the reason why it's so
dangerous is that means that

00:19:49.670 --> 00:19:51.720
kids could get married early.

00:19:51.720 --> 00:19:55.350
For girls, it means they would
have children early.

00:19:55.350 --> 00:19:58.750
And so we would have very early
pregnancies, which means

00:19:58.750 --> 00:20:00.550
that they would interrupt their
schooling, which means

00:20:00.550 --> 00:20:02.870
that they would be, typically,
quite a bit younger than their

00:20:02.870 --> 00:20:09.330
husbands, which changes their
status in the family, as we

00:20:09.330 --> 00:20:11.940
are going to see in a
minute, et cetera.

00:20:11.940 --> 00:20:18.330
So we decided to try and test
the impact of the ABCD program

00:20:18.330 --> 00:20:26.090
against doing nothing and
against another strategy,

00:20:26.090 --> 00:20:29.860
which is to basically make it
a little bit easier for kids

00:20:29.860 --> 00:20:31.470
to stay in school.

00:20:31.470 --> 00:20:33.220
How do you make it
a bit easier for

00:20:33.220 --> 00:20:33.630
kids to stay in school?

00:20:33.630 --> 00:20:36.870
You just pay the cost of staying
in school, which now

00:20:36.870 --> 00:20:40.090
is just like the uniform.

00:20:40.090 --> 00:20:43.760
So we ran an experiment with
Pascaline Dupas and Michael

00:20:43.760 --> 00:20:48.380
Kremer, a pretty big experiment,
376 schools, which

00:20:48.380 --> 00:20:50.810
were assigned to one
of four groups.

00:20:50.810 --> 00:20:52.270
One was a control group.

00:20:52.270 --> 00:20:54.300
One was a uniform group.

00:20:54.300 --> 00:20:58.290
And the other thing we did is
we wanted to test the ABCD

00:20:58.290 --> 00:21:02.400
strategy, so we accelerated
the training of teachers.

00:21:02.400 --> 00:21:06.120
Because, in principle, every
school is supposed to

00:21:06.120 --> 00:21:09.300
