option to switch toward
the casual sex.

00:40:49.500 --> 00:40:53.020
But here, they don't have the
option to switch, because they

00:40:53.020 --> 00:40:54.550
are scared of married
sex, because

00:40:54.550 --> 00:40:55.590
they don't want children.

00:40:55.590 --> 00:40:57.380
And they're scared of casual
sex, because they

00:40:57.380 --> 00:40:59.700
don't want an STD.

00:40:59.700 --> 00:41:02.280
And they think the probability
is high with casual sex.

00:41:02.280 --> 00:41:05.450
So the only thing they can do,
because they can't substitute

00:41:05.450 --> 00:41:08.810
between these two activities, is
either to have less sex or

00:41:08.810 --> 00:41:10.970
to use more contraception.

00:41:10.970 --> 00:41:14.230
And the teacher training,
itself, is not teaching them

00:41:14.230 --> 00:41:15.080
about contraception.

00:41:15.080 --> 00:41:17.720
But they all know, at some
level, that it's available,

00:41:17.720 --> 00:41:19.590
and that it prevents
both pregnancy

00:41:19.590 --> 00:41:21.570
and STDs, to a point.

00:41:26.140 --> 00:41:28.500
So this doesn't tell us you
shouldn't train the teachers.

00:41:28.500 --> 00:41:30.120
I think this tells us you
train the teachers with

00:41:30.120 --> 00:41:34.140
information that is actually
useful, actionable, which

00:41:34.140 --> 00:41:36.240
might not be such revolutionary
thinking.

00:41:36.240 --> 00:41:43.100
But when you spend a lot of
time in education/health

00:41:43.100 --> 00:41:48.540
circle in Kenya, you realize
it's actually a pretty big,

00:41:48.540 --> 00:41:49.810
pretty controversial
statement.

00:41:52.640 --> 00:41:55.700
So Pascaline Dupas, when she was
still a Ph.D. student, she

00:41:55.700 --> 00:42:00.260
worked in this project, to do
something else, which we talk

00:42:00.260 --> 00:42:01.990
about also a little bit
in the book, which is

00:42:01.990 --> 00:42:03.900
the sugar daddy project.

00:42:03.900 --> 00:42:06.632
And what the sugar daddy project
is, is to tell the

00:42:06.632 --> 00:42:12.410
kids that it is not true that
sex with older people is safe.

00:42:12.410 --> 00:42:16.020
In fact, older people are much
more likely to infected with

00:42:16.020 --> 00:42:18.710
HIV than younger people.

00:42:18.710 --> 00:42:23.590
So that's the information that
was given, plus a nice video

00:42:23.590 --> 00:42:28.850
about a girl who managed to trap
someone who wants to be a

00:42:28.850 --> 00:42:31.700
sugar daddy and something like
that, a very short, very quick

00:42:31.700 --> 00:42:32.660
intervention.

00:42:32.660 --> 00:42:35.800
A little film produced by
UNICEF and then these

00:42:35.800 --> 00:42:39.890
statistics, which is your
chance to get an STD.

00:42:39.890 --> 00:42:43.450
The infection rate of older men
is much higher than the

00:42:43.450 --> 00:42:47.240
infection rate of younger men.

00:42:47.240 --> 00:42:50.670
And sadly, the infection rate
of girls is also higher than

00:42:50.670 --> 00:42:53.460
that of boys, for the reason
that girls are more likely to

00:42:53.460 --> 00:42:56.590
have sex with older men, who
are likely to be infected.

00:42:56.590 --> 00:42:59.850
So you are telling the girls,
you should really have sex

00:42:59.850 --> 00:43:04.530
with the boys, because they are
safer than the men, not

00:43:04.530 --> 00:43:06.710
quite in so many words,
but making

00:43:06.710 --> 00:43:08.140
the information available.

00:43:08.140 --> 00:43:10.390
And you're also telling the
boys that these innocent

00:43:10.390 --> 00:43:13.600
looking girls actually
are probably more

00:43:13.600 --> 00:43:15.770
risky than you think.

00:43:15.770 --> 00:43:19.790
And this intervention was
actually quite effective at

00:43:19.790 --> 00:43:25.140
reducing sex with older
partners, as indicated by the

00:43:25.140 --> 00:43:27.540
number of pregnancies
with older dads.

00:43:27.540 --> 00:43:33.610
It reduced the pregnancy with
older dads by 66%, 2/3.

00:43:33.610 --> 00:43:37.430
So this is also another sign of
the fact that, if you tell

00:43:37.430 --> 00:43:40.820
people the right thing, like
people will react to what it

00:43:40.820 --> 00:43:41.380
is you tell them.

00:43:41.380 --> 00:43:43.320
If you tell people the wrong
thing, they're also going to

00:43:43.320 --> 00:43:43.870
react to it.

00:43:43.870 --> 00:43:46.000
But they'll not react to it
in a way that is very.

00:43:48.520 --> 00:43:51.490
You don't get that many more
HSV2, and you get many more

00:43:51.490 --> 00:43:55.060
kids who are married with
older men and have

00:43:55.060 --> 00:43:56.640
children too early.

00:43:56.640 --> 00:44:00.080
So that's, maybe, the biggest
lesson from this finding is

00:44:00.080 --> 00:44:01.890
you should tell people the truth
and assume that they

00:44:01.890 --> 00:44:04.690
will be able to make the
right decisions.

00:44:04.690 --> 00:44:09.470
You don't have to scare them
away into doing things.

00:44:09.470 --> 00:44:13.585
So that's for that.

00:44:17.510 --> 00:44:22.410
So I guess the key lesson
is fertility

00:44:22.410 --> 00:44:23.610
decisions are like others.

00:44:23.610 --> 00:44:25.740
We need to try and
understand them.

00:44:25.740 --> 00:44:29.380
And this is one area where
policies have been based on

00:44:29.380 --> 00:44:31.640
the assumption that
people are idiots.

00:44:31.640 --> 00:44:34.440
And that's, I think, a very bad
assumption in general and

00:44:34.440 --> 00:44:36.790
particularly, perhaps, in this
area, because it's a very

00:44:36.790 --> 00:44:40.210
important decision that people
are much more likely to take,

00:44:40.210 --> 00:44:43.290
with a lot of thinking and
with a lot of you.

00:44:43.290 --> 00:44:47.180
So that brings us, pretty
naturally, into the next

00:44:47.180 --> 00:44:52.710
topic, which is, if it's
a decision, inherently,

00:44:52.710 --> 00:44:57.370
fertility decisions are
decisions that are made by a

00:44:57.370 --> 00:45:00.300
man and a woman.

00:45:00.300 --> 00:45:03.000
But if we think about it, a lot
of the other decisions we

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:05.950
talked about in this class are
also decisions that are being

00:45:05.950 --> 00:45:07.740
made by a man and a woman.

00:45:07.740 --> 00:45:11.620
And we completely ignored that
our discussions so far.

00:45:11.620 --> 00:45:15.730
I've always talked about parents
decide how many,

00:45:15.730 --> 00:45:19.350
whether to immunize their kids,
how much to feed them,

00:45:19.350 --> 00:45:22.740
how many years of education they
should get, et cetera.

00:45:22.740 --> 00:45:26.370
And in this, I've ignored the
dynamic of the family.

00:45:26.370 --> 00:45:28.660
So now I want to spend
a bit of time--

00:45:28.660 --> 00:45:31.190
not much, but the rest
of this lecture--

00:45:31.190 --> 00:45:33.820
to talk about family
decisions.

00:45:57.990 --> 00:46:02.120
So the question, here, we're
going to ask is, how do

00:46:02.120 --> 00:46:03.370
families decide?

00:46:06.550 --> 00:46:09.190
So when we mean family,
we mean who?

00:46:09.190 --> 00:46:09.940
Like who decides?

00:46:09.940 --> 00:46:10.820
The dad decides.

00:46:10.820 --> 00:46:11.650
The mom decides.

00:46:11.650 --> 00:46:12.720
The mother-in-law decides.

00:46:12.720 --> 00:46:16.590
The kids, what do kids
have to play?

00:46:16.590 --> 00:46:19.180
They are relevant to all sorts
of decisions that are taken

00:46:19.180 --> 00:46:21.390
jointly by parents.

00:46:21.390 --> 00:46:23.790
Until now, we've ignored it.

00:46:23.790 --> 00:46:26.710
We've assumed that there was
something called, a family.

00:46:26.710 --> 00:46:29.710
And yet the family, we
know, is a group.

00:46:29.710 --> 00:46:35.580
So in what case would it be
legitimate to ignore the fact

00:46:35.580 --> 00:46:37.600
that the family is a
group of people?

00:46:37.600 --> 00:46:40.790
There are two cases where we
could say, well, we know it's

00:46:40.790 --> 00:46:42.040
a group, but we can ignore it.

00:46:45.432 --> 00:46:47.420
AUDIENCE: I would think all
families are the same?

00:46:47.420 --> 00:46:48.780
PROFESSOR: All family members.

00:46:48.780 --> 00:46:51.310
Like if we think that all family
members are the same,

00:46:51.310 --> 00:46:53.230
they all have the same
preferences, so they all want

00:46:53.230 --> 00:46:54.580
the same thing.

00:46:54.580 --> 00:46:58.850
So anybody who has been part of
a family, does this sound

00:46:58.850 --> 00:47:01.810
like a good approximation
to a family, the

00:47:01.810 --> 00:47:03.456
way a family functions?

00:47:03.456 --> 00:47:04.450
AUDIENCE: No.

00:47:04.450 --> 00:47:04.970
PROFESSOR: Not really.

00:47:04.970 --> 00:47:06.570
I think it's not the case
that there are no

00:47:06.570 --> 00:47:07.560
conflicts within families.

00:47:07.560 --> 00:47:09.700
People have different
views about how

00:47:09.700 --> 00:47:11.160
everything should be done.

00:47:11.160 --> 00:47:14.850
And the second way in which we
could ignore the fact that

00:47:14.850 --> 00:47:16.625
it's a collection of
individuals is?

00:47:19.385 --> 00:47:22.300
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:47:22.300 --> 00:47:24.380
PROFESSOR: If one person
made all the decisions.

00:47:24.380 --> 00:47:29.580
So we had the mother or the
father is like the person who

00:47:29.580 --> 00:47:32.220
makes all the decisions for
everyone, possibly taking into

00:47:32.220 --> 00:47:35.600
account people's preferences,
but not giving them a voice in

00:47:35.600 --> 00:47:36.990
how the decision
is being made.

00:47:40.450 --> 00:47:42.740
Does that sound a plausible
model of the family?

00:47:45.900 --> 00:47:47.600
AUDIENCE: At certain ages.

00:47:47.600 --> 00:47:48.040
PROFESSOR: Sorry?

00:47:48.040 --> 00:47:48.730
AUDIENCE: At certain ages.

00:47:48.730 --> 00:47:52.125
PROFESSOR: At certain ages, of
course, like the infant is not

00:47:52.125 --> 00:47:55.240
really in control, so someone
decides for them.

00:47:58.590 --> 00:47:59.020
Norm?

00:47:59.020 --> 00:48:02.124
AUDIENCE: Probably on the gender
breakdown, so the guys

00:48:02.124 --> 00:48:04.170
will decide, or the male
in the family will

00:48:04.170 --> 00:48:05.590
decide for the females.

00:48:05.590 --> 00:48:06.070
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:48:06.070 --> 00:48:11.380
So it might be that in some
societies, there is really a

00:48:11.380 --> 00:48:14.540
lot of control by the guys in
the family, as you say.

00:48:17.970 --> 00:48:20.500
But that will depend.

00:48:20.500 --> 00:48:24.100
Their society's say, you take
Pakistan or part of India,

00:48:24.100 --> 00:48:27.390
which will be more patriarchal
than Africa, where the African

00:48:27.390 --> 00:48:28.880
family is like--

00:48:28.880 --> 00:48:30.810
it depends where, of course--

00:48:30.810 --> 00:48:32.570
where there is more equality
between genders.

00:48:32.570 --> 00:48:35.500
So no one, maybe, is like
in a position to

00:48:35.500 --> 00:48:37.390
really, fully decide.

00:48:37.390 --> 00:48:40.680
So maybe the assumption that
one person decides for

00:48:40.680 --> 00:48:43.820
everyone is more plausible in
some cases, but we feel that

00:48:43.820 --> 00:48:46.480
it's not going to
be always true.

00:48:46.480 --> 00:48:50.300
And in a lot of cases, the
family is not one person.

00:48:50.300 --> 00:48:52.660
The family is a collection
of people.

00:48:52.660 --> 00:48:58.320
And they are trying
to fight it out.

00:48:58.320 --> 00:49:01.190
So women and men have different
preferences.

00:49:01.190 --> 00:49:03.910
For example, one area where
they have very different

00:49:03.910 --> 00:49:10.270
preferences is how many children
they want to have.

00:49:10.270 --> 00:49:12.600
So, for example, there was a
study in Zambia-- that I'm

00:49:12.600 --> 00:49:15.240
going to show you in a moment--
showing that women

00:49:15.240 --> 00:49:18.660
want to have much fewer
children than men.

00:49:18.660 --> 00:49:22.810
So one reason, of course, would
be that it's Zambia and

00:49:22.810 --> 00:49:26.390
the probability of dying in
childbirth is not 0, while if

00:49:26.390 --> 00:49:29.090
you're the woman, you're more
likely to be the one who is

00:49:29.090 --> 00:49:30.340
paying the cost of that.

00:49:32.960 --> 00:49:36.000
So as Norm mentioned, the family
is patriarchal in many

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:38.990
developing countries, so maybe
men take lot of decisions.

00:49:38.990 --> 00:49:42.050
But even there, you have,
usually, a little sphere, like

00:49:42.050 --> 00:49:44.500
how to buy the food, et cetera,
where it's really the

00:49:44.500 --> 00:49:46.680
woman who decides and
where bargaining

00:49:46.680 --> 00:49:49.400
could be taking place.

00:49:49.400 --> 00:49:52.050
So how do we test this?

00:49:52.050 --> 00:49:53.270
How do we know?

00:49:53.270 --> 00:49:55.840
How we can we try and see
whether the family is

00:49:55.840 --> 00:49:59.680
patriarchal, is unitary, either
everybody agrees or

00:49:59.680 --> 00:50:02.300
someone decides for everyone?

00:50:02.300 --> 00:50:06.050
So if the family behaves like
one individual, we could

00:50:06.050 --> 00:50:08.020
analyze the decision problem
of a family--

00:50:08.020 --> 00:50:10.920
for example, how much food to
buy, whether to send the kids

00:50:10.920 --> 00:50:13.790
to school, how many children
to how, et cetera--

00:50:13.790 --> 00:50:16.770
like the problem of
one single person.

00:50:16.770 --> 00:50:19.440
So the only thing that should
matter to a single person,

00:50:19.440 --> 00:50:22.760
and, therefore, to the family
in this context, is the

00:50:22.760 --> 00:50:27.730
family's overall income,
the prices of things--

00:50:27.730 --> 00:50:32.280
how expensive it is to buy
whichever types of thing,

00:50:32.280 --> 00:50:35.320
school fees, et cetera--

00:50:35.320 --> 00:50:41.310
and information that you have,
to everyone in the family.

00:50:41.310 --> 00:50:42.980
But if the family
is not unitary.

00:50:42.980 --> 00:50:46.380
It's what we call this model,
where one person decides for

00:50:46.380 --> 00:50:47.900
everyone or everybody agrees.

00:50:47.900 --> 00:50:51.640
We call this the unitary model,
like there is unity in

00:50:51.640 --> 00:50:52.820
the family.

00:50:52.820 --> 00:50:55.780
So if the family is not unitary,
than other things are

00:50:55.780 --> 00:50:57.710
going to start to matter.

00:50:57.710 --> 00:51:00.740
So, for example, it's not only
the overall income that is

00:51:00.740 --> 00:51:04.730
going to matter, but who
brings what share.

00:51:04.730 --> 00:51:09.680
Because they can now, say, well,
if you don't do what I

00:51:09.680 --> 00:51:11.690
want to do, then I'm just
going to take my

00:51:11.690 --> 00:51:13.430
income and go away.

00:51:13.430 --> 00:51:16.220
So now it's not the overall
income that's going to matter,

00:51:16.220 --> 00:51:18.540
it's the share of the income.

00:51:18.540 --> 00:51:21.820
So again, we could see men
taking much more decisions,

00:51:21.820 --> 00:51:24.670
that's because they are bring
more of the income.

00:51:24.670 --> 00:51:30.300
And we could see, maybe, that
when woman bring more income,

00:51:30.300 --> 00:51:33.720
they would be able to
take more decisions.

00:51:33.720 --> 00:51:36.910
The second thing that might
matter is private information.

00:51:36.910 --> 00:51:39.480
So if you know that the family
is not unitary, and you find

00:51:39.480 --> 00:51:42.810
something out, you might
keep it for you.

00:51:42.810 --> 00:51:46.160
Because that gives you some
power to make some decisions.

00:51:46.160 --> 00:51:49.770
So let's look at whether we
find evidence that private

00:51:49.770 --> 00:51:52.150
information, that is information
that one member

00:51:52.150 --> 00:51:55.630
has and not the other, makes a
difference in decisions and

00:51:55.630 --> 00:51:58.610
whether it's who brings
the income to

00:51:58.610 --> 00:52:01.050
family matters as well.

00:52:01.050 --> 00:52:02.300
Let's look at these
two things.

00:52:04.930 --> 00:52:08.970
So private information, let's
look at fertility.

00:52:08.970 --> 00:52:13.060
So I was telling this data from
Zambia showing that women

00:52:13.060 --> 00:52:16.010
want to have fewer
kids than men.

00:52:16.010 --> 00:52:18.630
And in fact, they report hiding
contraceptives from

00:52:18.630 --> 00:52:21.280
their husbands.

00:52:21.280 --> 00:52:26.140
So in that case, you could
ask a question.

00:52:26.140 --> 00:52:30.990
If I provide information to
women about contraceptives,

00:52:30.990 --> 00:52:34.150
would it make a difference if
I provide it to the woman

00:52:34.150 --> 00:52:39.260
alone or if I provide it
together to women and men?

00:52:39.260 --> 00:52:43.050
So under the unitary model,
what would we expect?

00:52:43.050 --> 00:52:47.750
AUDIENCE: Whoever the head of
the household is, [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:47.750 --> 00:52:49.620
PROFESSOR: Yeah, whoever we give
it to, even if it's not

00:52:49.620 --> 00:52:51.270
the head, we give it
to the woman, she's

00:52:51.270 --> 00:52:52.780
going to tell the husband.

00:52:52.780 --> 00:52:54.330
So it should make
no difference.

00:52:54.330 --> 00:52:56.785
Or maybe it would even have a
bigger effect to give it to

00:52:56.785 --> 00:52:59.390
the men, because they are more
likely to understand, they're

00:52:59.390 --> 00:53:01.690
more likely to be involved,
et cetera.

00:53:01.690 --> 00:53:05.100
So a lot of family planning
policies are now saying, we

00:53:05.100 --> 00:53:06.980
have to involve the men.

00:53:06.980 --> 00:53:08.500
Because after all, the men
have something to do with

00:53:08.500 --> 00:53:09.140
contraception.

00:53:09.140 --> 00:53:09.830
That's the idea.

00:53:09.830 --> 00:53:11.870
Let's involve the men, and they
would be more likely to

00:53:11.870 --> 00:53:13.210
be informed.

00:53:13.210 --> 00:53:23.540
On the other hand, if it is the
case that women are more

00:53:23.540 --> 00:53:27.770
likely to want fewer children,
then involving only the woman,

00:53:27.770 --> 00:53:32.730
it gives her an option to hide
the contraception from her

00:53:32.730 --> 00:53:34.280
husband and, therefore,
potentially,

00:53:34.280 --> 00:53:35.430
to have fewer kids.

00:53:35.430 --> 00:53:37.050
So it could really
cut both ways.

00:53:37.050 --> 00:53:39.910
In the unitary model, you would
expect no difference or

00:53:39.910 --> 00:53:42.920
maybe doing it to both together
would be better.

00:53:42.920 --> 00:53:47.740
Or it would have a larger
effect, because the

00:53:47.740 --> 00:53:49.190
information would be
more likely to be

00:53:49.190 --> 00:53:50.730
diffused in the family.

00:53:50.730 --> 00:53:52.750
Under the non-unitary model,
maybe the woman

00:53:52.750 --> 00:53:54.750
would matter more.

00:53:54.750 --> 00:53:56.280
So what do you think
is happening?

00:53:59.220 --> 00:54:00.470
What's your bet?

00:54:03.502 --> 00:54:05.306
AUDIENCE: The women use
it more when their

00:54:05.306 --> 00:54:06.460
husbands don't know.

00:54:06.460 --> 00:54:07.440
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:54:07.440 --> 00:54:11.210
What they find is that women
use it much more when their

00:54:11.210 --> 00:54:12.180
husband doesn't how.

00:54:12.180 --> 00:54:12.960
So they did that?

00:54:12.960 --> 00:54:17.620
Well, they ran an experiment
where they provided people a

00:54:17.620 --> 00:54:20.480
voucher to skip the queue.

00:54:20.480 --> 00:54:22.780
Because in Zambia, in principle,
you are allowed to

00:54:22.780 --> 00:54:25.030
have contraception, et cetera.

00:54:25.030 --> 00:54:27.630
But in practice, it
takes a long time.

00:54:27.630 --> 00:54:28.510
The nurse calls you.

00:54:28.510 --> 00:54:31.430
Once you've come, if you don't
have your clothes for an

00:54:31.430 --> 00:54:32.880
examination.

00:54:32.880 --> 00:54:35.730
So people don't really go
to the family planning.

00:54:35.730 --> 00:54:40.850
So here, it's a voucher for
first class treatment, no need

00:54:40.850 --> 00:54:46.170
to bring your clothes and
a good, nice setting.

00:54:46.170 --> 00:54:49.350
So they did that.

00:54:49.350 --> 00:54:50.510
I don't know if it was half.

00:54:50.510 --> 00:54:54.550
But the separated the group in
two, one where they gave the

00:54:54.550 --> 00:54:57.750
voucher to the wife, alone, and
one where they gave it to

00:54:57.750 --> 00:54:59.000
wife and husband together.

00:55:01.410 --> 00:55:04.190
And so the question is whether
women are more likely to take

00:55:04.190 --> 00:55:08.440
care of their contraception,
whether they're more likely to

00:55:08.440 --> 00:55:10.890
be able to control their
fertility in one

00:55:10.890 --> 00:55:13.130
case than in the other.

00:55:13.130 --> 00:55:18.050
So that's what the find for the
take-up of the voucher.

00:55:18.050 --> 00:55:21.850
So the first two columns
are whether or not

00:55:21.850 --> 00:55:23.970
you redeemed a voucher.

00:55:23.970 --> 00:55:29.200
And the second two are whether
or not you get an injection of

00:55:29.200 --> 00:55:33.670
contraception, which is a method
of contraception that

00:55:33.670 --> 00:55:35.770
you can hide easily.

00:55:35.770 --> 00:55:37.580
Because you got the injection.

00:55:37.580 --> 00:55:39.940
No one knows that you
are not fertile for

00:55:39.940 --> 00:55:42.180
the next three months.

00:55:42.180 --> 00:55:45.590
And what you find is that people
are more likely to

00:55:45.590 --> 00:55:48.880
redeem the voucher in the
individual treatment than in

00:55:48.880 --> 00:55:50.920
the couple treatment .

00:55:50.920 --> 00:55:54.640
And they are more likely to
receive the concealable method

00:55:54.640 --> 00:55:59.240
in the individual treatment than
in a couple treatment.

00:55:59.240 --> 00:56:05.220
So the effects are of the
order of, let's say, 55%

00:56:05.220 --> 00:56:08.200
received a voucher in individual
versus 42%.

00:56:08.200 --> 00:56:11.800
So these are not negligible
effects.

00:56:11.800 --> 00:56:15.010
So it seems that it matters how
you provide information.

00:56:15.010 --> 00:56:20.260
It matters also for the number
of kids that people have.

00:56:20.260 --> 00:56:24.270
So this is the fraction of
births, in the months

00:56:24.270 --> 00:56:28.450
following the treatment, among
women, who said, at baseline,

00:56:28.450 --> 00:56:30.760
that they did not want
any more births.

00:56:30.760 --> 00:56:36.000
So you can think of them as
unwanted pregnancies.

00:56:36.000 --> 00:56:38.820
So six months later,
of course, you

00:56:38.820 --> 00:56:40.070
should see no effect.

00:56:46.045 --> 00:56:48.650
The couple treatment, which is
the red line, is a little

00:56:48.650 --> 00:56:51.410
below, but that's not due to
the treatment, because it's

00:56:51.410 --> 00:56:53.990
six months later.

00:56:53.990 --> 00:56:57.000
And then at nine months,
the couple cross.

00:56:57.000 --> 00:57:01.920
And the red line is above the
blue line for a few months,

00:57:01.920 --> 00:57:05.950
which reflects about three
months of Depo-Provera use.

00:57:05.950 --> 00:57:08.160
And then what happened is that
the effect on that, it

00:57:08.160 --> 00:57:09.620
disappears subsequently.

00:57:09.620 --> 00:57:12.420
And it goes up a lot for both.

00:57:12.420 --> 00:57:17.740
And the reason is that there was
a policy change in Zambia.

00:57:17.740 --> 00:57:21.040
All of the injectable were taken
away from the market.

00:57:21.040 --> 00:57:26.310
So any effect of the treatment
goes away, because after your

00:57:26.310 --> 00:57:29.230
first injection, you could
not get the second one.

00:57:29.230 --> 00:57:36.860
So we should expect an effect
in the 9 to 14 month, after

00:57:36.860 --> 00:57:39.950
the treatment, which is
exactly what we find.

00:57:39.950 --> 00:57:45.310
So if we look at the number of
unwanted births that were

00:57:45.310 --> 00:57:47.140
prevented--

00:57:47.140 --> 00:57:48.630
I actually don't remember
exactly the number.

00:57:48.630 --> 00:57:50.950
But it's a fair number of
unwanted births that were

00:57:50.950 --> 00:57:56.750
prevented by going from
couple treatment to

00:57:56.750 --> 00:57:57.780
the woman only treatment.

00:57:57.780 --> 00:58:01.000
So that's the first indication
that the family is not

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:04.380
unitary, because who you are
giving information to changes

00:58:04.380 --> 00:58:05.210
the outcome.

00:58:05.210 --> 00:58:06.850
So people hide information.

00:58:10.560 --> 00:58:13.560
The second information
is what economists

00:58:13.560 --> 00:58:15.870
call bargaining power.

00:58:15.870 --> 00:58:18.650
So even when the information
set is the same for both

00:58:18.650 --> 00:58:20.560
partners, they might start
to bargain over a family

00:58:20.560 --> 00:58:25.380
decision, who works, how hard,
how many children to have, how

00:58:25.380 --> 00:58:27.710
much to feed the children,
how much to educate the

00:58:27.710 --> 00:58:29.520
children, et cetera.

00:58:29.520 --> 00:58:32.860
So the bargaining power is your
ability to weigh-in on

00:58:32.860 --> 00:58:35.280
the family decision, if the
family decision are the

00:58:35.280 --> 00:58:38.560
process of these discussions.

00:58:38.560 --> 00:58:41.630
So what would affect a woman's
bargaining power, other than

00:58:41.630 --> 00:58:42.920
the information she has?

00:58:46.310 --> 00:58:49.020
So we already mentioned
an income.

00:58:49.020 --> 00:58:51.992
What else could be there?

00:58:51.992 --> 00:58:54.990
If you have good eyesight, you
can read it on the slide, but

00:58:54.990 --> 00:58:56.670
you can also think
about it instead.

00:59:00.135 --> 00:59:03.590
AUDIENCE: Maybe divorce
policy?

00:59:03.590 --> 00:59:04.760
PROFESSOR: Absolutely right.

00:59:04.760 --> 00:59:07.400
Divorce policy will affect
bargaining power.

00:59:07.400 --> 00:59:08.863
And how does it work?

00:59:08.863 --> 00:59:11.761
AUDIENCE: Depending on how
they allocate the family

00:59:11.761 --> 00:59:15.142
resources after divorce,
I don't know there.

00:59:15.142 --> 00:59:18.523
But I know in the past, in the
US, they would allocate it

00:59:18.523 --> 00:59:19.972
mostly to the man.

00:59:19.972 --> 00:59:21.920
And now, in a lot of
states, it's 50-50.

00:59:21.920 --> 00:59:22.410
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:59:22.410 --> 00:59:24.600
If you live in a divorce regime,
where all of the

00:59:24.600 --> 00:59:28.060
assets, and maybe the control
over the children, goes to the

00:59:28.060 --> 00:59:31.910
man, then for a woman to
divorce is a disaster.

00:59:31.910 --> 00:59:34.080
So when the take decisions, when
they bargain, they are

00:59:34.080 --> 00:59:36.980
thinking, what is my
outside option?

00:59:36.980 --> 00:59:40.520
And if I'm thinking my outside
option is absolutely horrible,

00:59:40.520 --> 00:59:42.640
then I have to agree
to whatever

00:59:42.640 --> 00:59:44.670
the husband is proposing.

00:59:44.670 --> 00:59:48.070
So the divorce laws are going
to make a difference.

00:59:48.070 --> 00:59:52.620
How much of the commons assets
can the woman get back, and

00:59:52.620 --> 00:59:55.020
how much control of kids
could she have?

00:59:55.020 --> 00:59:58.430
And in fact, it's been shown,
in the US, that when the

00:59:58.430 --> 01:00:01.150
change that you talked about
was implemented, it was

01:00:01.150 --> 01:00:03.860
implemented in different states
at different times.

01:00:03.860 --> 01:00:07.770
So you can trace what happened
to women, in particular, to

01:00:07.770 --> 01:00:10.230
decisions that are more in the
interest of the woman.

01:00:10.230 --> 01:00:13.190
You can see that the decisions,
within the

01:00:13.190 --> 01:00:16.390
household, improved in favor of
the woman when the divorce

01:00:16.390 --> 01:00:20.500
law improved to give
women more rights.

01:00:20.500 --> 01:00:22.628
So divorce law is one.

01:00:22.628 --> 01:00:25.098
AUDIENCE: Actually,
like health?

01:00:25.098 --> 01:00:28.925
So if the husband is in really
bad health, the woman probably

01:00:28.925 --> 01:00:31.520
has a lot of power
in the family.

01:00:31.520 --> 01:00:33.090
PROFESSOR: If the husband
has bad health, the

01:00:33.090 --> 01:00:34.340
woman has more power.

01:00:34.340 --> 01:00:36.260
Yes, that could be one.

01:00:36.260 --> 01:00:39.490
Maybe because his outside
option is now very bad,

01:00:39.490 --> 01:00:42.620
because A, he couldn't get
married to someone else,

01:00:42.620 --> 01:00:43.460
because he is so sick.

01:00:43.460 --> 01:00:50.330
B, he couldn't get by himself,
so he has to kind of be nice

01:00:50.330 --> 01:00:53.570
so that she will continue
to take care of him.

01:00:53.570 --> 01:00:55.170
AUDIENCE: So this slightly
related to a lot of them.

01:00:57.825 --> 01:01:01.730
If you came from a wealthy
family or came from a family

01:01:01.730 --> 01:01:05.322
with a status, the husband
couldn't get anything from the

01:01:05.322 --> 01:01:06.768
family, but just so as
not to embarrass

01:01:06.768 --> 01:01:08.220
himself in the society?

01:01:08.220 --> 01:01:08.690
PROFESSOR: Yes, exactly.

01:01:08.690 --> 01:01:12.560
So the family you're coming from
will influence bargaining

01:01:12.560 --> 01:01:17.550
power, because, maybe, not
wanting to embarrass himself.

01:01:17.550 --> 01:01:20.500
Also, because it could be a
threat that my very strong

01:01:20.500 --> 01:01:24.060
brothers are going to break
your kneecaps if you don't

01:01:24.060 --> 01:01:25.650
behave with me.

01:01:25.650 --> 01:01:28.070
So that creates like
an outside option.

01:01:28.070 --> 01:01:31.350
Also, in case of divorce, again,
it gives you a chance

01:01:31.350 --> 01:01:34.350
to come back to something,
whereas if you have no family,

01:01:34.350 --> 01:01:36.100
then you have no options.

01:01:36.100 --> 01:01:40.030
So that's very good,
your family,

01:01:40.030 --> 01:01:41.580
where people came from.

01:01:41.580 --> 01:01:42.938
What else could we have?

01:01:42.938 --> 01:01:46.354
AUDIENCE: The relative level
of education [INAUDIBLE].

01:01:46.354 --> 01:01:50.746
If she's just been to high
school, [INAUDIBLE]

01:01:50.746 --> 01:01:53.186
make that economic decision.

01:01:53.186 --> 01:01:58.554
She may not have the mental
leverage to say, what I'm

01:01:58.554 --> 01:02:00.506
saying makes more sense.

01:02:00.506 --> 01:02:01.030
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:02:01.030 --> 01:02:01.820
So that's very good.

01:02:01.820 --> 01:02:05.760
So the relative level of
education will matter, both

01:02:05.760 --> 01:02:07.820
because, again, it creates
some different outside

01:02:07.820 --> 01:02:09.750
options, because with a
high school dropout,

01:02:09.750 --> 01:02:11.040
what would you do?

01:02:11.040 --> 01:02:12.820
You're kind of dependent.

01:02:12.820 --> 01:02:16.230
And the other point you're
making, which is not about

01:02:16.230 --> 01:02:18.940
outside options, but even
your ability to bargain.

01:02:18.940 --> 01:02:21.510
You might not feel confident.

01:02:21.510 --> 01:02:23.810
When someone tells you that I
know better, you might feel

01:02:23.810 --> 01:02:26.080
like, yeah, maybe
you know better.

01:02:26.080 --> 01:02:27.791
Good.

01:02:27.791 --> 01:02:31.767
AUDIENCE: Is it possible to
consider that a woman could

01:02:31.767 --> 01:02:35.246
tell her husband, we won't have
intercourse if you don't

01:02:35.246 --> 01:02:37.750
do this and that.

01:02:37.750 --> 01:02:37.980
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:02:37.980 --> 01:02:45.430
Not only is it possible, but I
think that's a pretty frequent

01:02:45.430 --> 01:02:47.440
bargaining technique.

01:02:47.440 --> 01:02:52.830
So, in that case, if that's the
bargaining technique, then

01:02:52.830 --> 01:02:56.830
you would think how attractive
each partner is and how long

01:02:56.830 --> 01:02:58.890
they've been in a relationship
and things like that

01:02:58.890 --> 01:02:59.720
are going to matter.

01:02:59.720 --> 01:03:02.010
Because the level of the threat
is also whether or not

01:03:02.010 --> 01:03:06.170
you think it's a problem or
you could figure something

01:03:06.170 --> 01:03:07.420
else out if necessary.

01:03:11.610 --> 01:03:14.338
What else would we have?

01:03:20.430 --> 01:03:23.920
Well, one more is your ability
to earn an independent income.

01:03:23.920 --> 01:03:26.760
So that's related to the point
you're making about education.

01:03:26.760 --> 01:03:33.660
But it could also be just labor
market opportunities for

01:03:33.660 --> 01:03:34.630
men and women.

01:03:34.630 --> 01:03:38.280
So for example, if you live in
a society where women cannot

01:03:38.280 --> 01:03:42.680
get jobs, because say there is
[INAUDIBLE], then what will

01:03:42.680 --> 01:03:45.040
the woman do without husbands?

01:03:45.040 --> 01:03:46.350
There would be a big problem.

01:03:46.350 --> 01:03:51.370
Whereas if you live in a society
like here, where you

01:03:51.370 --> 01:03:57.580
could get a job, if you needed
to, then that changes your

01:03:57.580 --> 01:04:00.950
level of outside options, and,
therefore, changes the way the

01:04:00.950 --> 01:04:03.010
negotiations would be made.

01:04:03.010 --> 01:04:06.120
Another one is the
marriage market.

01:04:06.120 --> 01:04:09.130
Is it possible for a woman to
get married or for a man to

01:04:09.130 --> 01:04:11.310
get married after a divorce?

01:04:11.310 --> 01:04:13.190
There are some places
where it's harder.

01:04:13.190 --> 01:04:19.150
What is the gender ratio, how
many women there are for men?

01:04:19.150 --> 01:04:23.350
If you are in, for example, an
immigrant community, where the

01:04:23.350 --> 01:04:27.540
ratio of men to woman is very
skewed, because a lot of men

01:04:27.540 --> 01:04:32.190
have come, new men have come,
then the woman can threaten to

01:04:32.190 --> 01:04:34.090
get married to any of
those available

01:04:34.090 --> 01:04:35.990
boys within the community.

01:04:35.990 --> 01:04:38.250
That would increase their
bargaining power within the

01:04:38.250 --> 01:04:42.790
family compared to a situation
which is more even.

01:04:42.790 --> 01:04:47.352
People said that about China,
today, that one kind of

01:04:47.352 --> 01:04:51.130
strange consequences of the fact
that the gender ratio are

01:04:51.130 --> 01:04:54.140
completely skewed, due to
selective abortion and things

01:04:54.140 --> 01:04:57.040
like, it means that women,
actually, are in short supply.

01:04:57.040 --> 01:05:02.090
And therefore, it's getting
easier to marry them.

01:05:02.090 --> 01:05:05.210
And they have a lot of
bargaining power within the

01:05:05.210 --> 01:05:09.090
family, because there's no
substitute for them.

01:05:09.090 --> 01:05:11.450
So all of these things
would matter.

01:05:11.450 --> 01:05:18.120
So let's focus on one, for the
purpose of this, which is how

01:05:18.120 --> 01:05:21.500
much money women and men bring
to the family, and, in

01:05:21.500 --> 01:05:24.810
particular, how much money
they would have access to

01:05:24.810 --> 01:05:26.190
should they leave
the marriage.

01:05:29.080 --> 01:05:32.640
That's going to matter
for family decisions.

01:05:32.640 --> 01:05:37.160
So policy makers are very
convinced it's the case.

01:05:37.160 --> 01:05:40.460
So for example, all the cash
transfer programs that exist

01:05:40.460 --> 01:05:45.160
in Latin America, to encourage
schooling and health--

01:05:45.160 --> 01:05:47.685
like the PROGRESA program in
Mexico, that we discussed in

01:05:47.685 --> 01:05:49.220
the case of education--

01:05:49.220 --> 01:05:51.570
they tend to always give
the money to women.

01:05:51.570 --> 01:05:55.190
On the ground that A, women will
make a bigger use of the

01:05:55.190 --> 01:05:57.830
money, and B, that's going to
increase their bargaining

01:05:57.830 --> 01:06:00.410
power and, therefore, increase
all decisions.

01:06:00.410 --> 01:06:05.720
So there is very benign sexism
going on around in the policy

01:06:05.720 --> 01:06:08.900
world that women are generally
better people, which I don't

01:06:08.900 --> 01:06:10.160
necessarily disagree with.

01:06:10.160 --> 01:06:14.820
But it should be looked
into a little bit.

01:06:14.820 --> 01:06:17.680
So another one that is very
much inspired by this is

01:06:17.680 --> 01:06:18.800
microcredit.

01:06:18.800 --> 01:06:21.000
Microcredit claims,
the world-wide,

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:22.780
are almost all women.

01:06:22.780 --> 01:06:25.370
Part of the reason is that
women are believed to be

01:06:25.370 --> 01:06:27.350
better at repaying.

01:06:27.350 --> 01:06:29.530
But part of the reason is also
that it was believed that it

01:06:29.530 --> 01:06:33.360
was a way to introduce some
changes, within their

01:06:33.360 --> 01:06:35.780
families, by giving power
to the family.

01:06:35.780 --> 01:06:39.470
So does it matter who gets money
or doesn't get money?

01:06:39.470 --> 01:06:43.000
I want to give one example to
prove my point that women are

01:06:43.000 --> 01:06:45.760
better people than men.

01:06:45.760 --> 01:06:50.840
Looking at one example where
money went into the household,

01:06:50.840 --> 01:06:56.560
either with the men or with
women, which is the end of

01:06:56.560 --> 01:06:59.930
Apartheid in South Africa.

01:06:59.930 --> 01:07:02.150
They took a pension program,
which existed for white

01:07:02.150 --> 01:07:05.270
people, which was, for white
people, a very small pension

01:07:05.270 --> 01:07:10.480
program, in that it was not
a lot of money for them.

01:07:10.480 --> 01:07:13.910
And also, almost no one was
eligible, because you couldn't

01:07:13.910 --> 01:07:16.070
be eligible if you had
a private pension.

01:07:16.070 --> 01:07:18.050
And most people have
private pensions.

01:07:18.050 --> 01:07:21.820
So it was smallish program on
the side, a little bit like we

01:07:21.820 --> 01:07:24.700
have here with minimum,
old-age security.

01:07:24.700 --> 01:07:28.640
But at the end of Apartheid, the
new government had to make

01:07:28.640 --> 01:07:31.970
a decision about, should we can
the program or should we

01:07:31.970 --> 01:07:33.870
expand it to the black
South Africans?

01:07:33.870 --> 01:07:36.970
Of course, they're not going to
keep two separate programs.

01:07:36.970 --> 01:07:41.380
And they decided to expand it,
because it was believed,

01:07:41.380 --> 01:07:44.600
rightly, that the older people,
who would be eligible

01:07:44.600 --> 01:07:47.240
for this program, are precisely
the people who

01:07:47.240 --> 01:07:50.790
suffered the most from
Apartheid, for

01:07:50.790 --> 01:07:52.570
their entire lifetime.

01:07:52.570 --> 01:07:54.210
So they expanded the program.

01:07:54.210 --> 01:07:58.650
And every man above 65 and
every woman about 60 is

01:07:58.650 --> 01:08:00.770
eligible for the program
unless they

01:08:00.770 --> 01:08:01.560
have a private pension.

01:08:01.560 --> 01:08:04.220
And very few of the black people
had a private pension.

01:08:04.220 --> 01:08:07.160
So about 85 to 90% percent of
people who are eligible

01:08:07.160 --> 01:08:08.950
actually get the program.

01:08:08.950 --> 01:08:11.200
So the old-age pension program,
which is still there

01:08:11.200 --> 01:08:13.800
today, it's a huge, huge deal.

01:08:13.800 --> 01:08:15.220
It's a lot of money.

01:08:15.220 --> 01:08:18.470
And it's very important
for the families.

01:08:18.470 --> 01:08:22.880
And, of course, a lot of the
older people don't live alone.

01:08:22.880 --> 01:08:25.370
They live with children or they
live with grandchildren.

01:08:25.370 --> 01:08:28.460
And in particular, in South
Africa, it is quite frequent

01:08:28.460 --> 01:08:32.680
that you have skip-generation
households, where you have a

01:08:32.680 --> 01:08:36.210
grandparent, no parent,
and the kids.

01:08:36.210 --> 01:08:40.290
This is for two reasons, one is
HIV/AIDS, which has killed

01:08:40.290 --> 01:08:42.460
a lot of the middle
generation.

01:08:42.460 --> 01:08:46.979
And the other is the way the
society was structured under

01:08:46.979 --> 01:08:49.870
Apartheid, people couldn't bring
their family when they

01:08:49.870 --> 01:08:51.529
went to work in the city.

01:08:51.529 --> 01:08:56.739
So they went alone, and they
left the kids behind with the

01:08:56.739 --> 01:08:57.689
grandparents.

01:08:57.689 --> 01:09:01.520
So for this reason, about a
quarter of kids, aged 0 to 5,

01:09:01.520 --> 01:09:03.550
live with a grandparent.

01:09:03.550 --> 01:09:05.314
And that grandparent
can either be a man

01:09:05.314 --> 01:09:08.170
or it can be a woman.

01:09:08.170 --> 01:09:10.540
And the question we can ask is,
does it make a difference,

01:09:10.540 --> 01:09:13.910
when this pension program comes
in, in 1993, if you

01:09:13.910 --> 01:09:17.310
happen to live with no one or
with a grandparent, who

01:09:17.310 --> 01:09:21.779
becomes eligible, or with a
grandfather or a grandmother?

01:09:21.779 --> 01:09:29.060
So of course, one problem is
that the families who have a

01:09:29.060 --> 01:09:33.359
grandfather are different from
the family who don't have a

01:09:33.359 --> 01:09:36.160
grandfather.

01:09:36.160 --> 01:09:47.204
So what we can look at is, let's
take a sample of kids

01:09:47.204 --> 01:09:54.980
who live with a grandfather, but
let's compare the one who

01:09:54.980 --> 01:09:59.030
lives with a grandfather who is,
let's say, 55, versus one

01:09:59.030 --> 01:10:04.920
who is 65 or a grandfather who
is 50 to 64 versus 66.

01:10:04.920 --> 01:10:07.780
So in both cases, there
is a grandfather.

01:10:07.780 --> 01:10:10.090
But one is just short
of being eligible.

01:10:10.090 --> 01:10:12.770
And one is just eligible.

01:10:12.770 --> 01:10:15.880
So other characteristics of the
family should be more or

01:10:15.880 --> 01:10:16.990
less constant.

01:10:16.990 --> 01:10:19.360
It just happened that your
age is a good thing.

01:10:19.360 --> 01:10:21.600
And of course, people couldn't
really predict that this

01:10:21.600 --> 01:10:25.780
pension was coming, so the kid
lives with a grandfather and,

01:10:25.780 --> 01:10:28.920
oh, he becomes just eligible
or is not yet eligible.

01:10:28.920 --> 01:10:32.520
The same thing with the
grandmother but around 60.

01:10:32.520 --> 01:10:34.290
So this is what this is doing.

01:10:34.290 --> 01:10:36.360
This is looking at weight
for height.

01:10:36.360 --> 01:10:38.485
So this is short trend
measure of nutrition.

01:10:43.095 --> 01:10:44.880
As soon as you start
eating better, you

01:10:44.880 --> 01:10:47.190
weight for height improves.

01:10:47.190 --> 01:10:52.510
And in orange, we have
the boys, and, in

01:10:52.510 --> 01:10:54.980
yellow, we have the girls.

01:10:54.980 --> 01:10:58.010
And you can see that.

01:10:58.010 --> 01:10:59.000
So what can you see?

01:10:59.000 --> 01:11:00.743
Can you interpret this?

01:11:03.550 --> 01:11:07.644
AUDIENCE: So this bar is
higher for eligible

01:11:07.644 --> 01:11:12.370
grandmothers that took all
their grandsons in.

01:11:12.370 --> 01:11:13.200
PROFESSOR: [INAUDIBLE]

01:11:13.200 --> 01:11:15.088
AUDIENCE: Heavier grandsons
and granddaughters.

01:11:15.088 --> 01:11:19.336
And my guess is that, because
they're eligible earlier, they

01:11:19.336 --> 01:11:22.130
have more to give earlier.

01:11:22.130 --> 01:11:23.090
PROFESSOR: So this
is right after

01:11:23.090 --> 01:11:26.660
eligibility in both cases.

01:11:26.660 --> 01:11:28.710
So we don't have a longer time.

01:11:28.710 --> 01:11:29.080
Yeah?

01:11:29.080 --> 01:11:32.050
AUDIENCE: Well, it's just to
show that grandmothers seem to

01:11:32.050 --> 01:11:34.525
care more about their
grandchildren than

01:11:34.525 --> 01:11:37.495
grandfathers do when they
become eligible.

01:11:37.495 --> 01:11:40.465
And then you can also
see the bias.

01:11:40.465 --> 01:11:44.920
So for grandmothers, it seems
like they treat girls better.

01:11:44.920 --> 01:11:48.880
And grandfathers also
treat girls better.

01:11:48.880 --> 01:11:50.960
PROFESSOR: So, basically, we
don't have much for the

01:11:50.960 --> 01:11:52.950
grandfathers.

01:11:52.950 --> 01:11:56.080
So the grandfather doesn't seem
to be using the money to

01:11:56.080 --> 01:11:57.760
be feeding the kids.

01:11:57.760 --> 01:12:01.210
And we have up a much larger
effect for the grandmothers,

01:12:01.210 --> 01:12:04.040
particularly for the girls.

01:12:04.040 --> 01:12:06.750
And some effects for the boys,
but only half the size.

01:12:06.750 --> 01:12:10.102
AUDIENCE: Now why is it the case
that the grandsons are

01:12:10.102 --> 01:12:15.310
worse off when their eligible
grandfathers [INAUDIBLE]?

01:12:15.310 --> 01:12:17.650
PROFESSOR: So if we had the
confidence interval bar on

01:12:17.650 --> 01:12:20.310
this graph, you would see that
this is not significant.

01:12:20.310 --> 01:12:23.830
So this is kind of same-ish.

01:12:23.830 --> 01:12:26.330
No eligible grandparents and
the bars for eligible

01:12:26.330 --> 01:12:29.340
grandfather are around
the same magnitude.

01:12:29.340 --> 01:12:32.010
What is really different
is the girls with the

01:12:32.010 --> 01:12:33.620
grandmother.

01:12:33.620 --> 01:12:36.584
And the boys to some extent, but
it's about half the size.

01:12:36.584 --> 01:12:39.795
AUDIENCE: So could there be an
effect in that, when you have

01:12:39.795 --> 01:12:41.928
an eligible grandfather, they're
older, so that they'll

01:12:41.928 --> 01:12:43.560
have to spend more of
their pension on

01:12:43.560 --> 01:12:45.340
like their own stuff?

01:12:45.340 --> 01:12:45.980
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:12:45.980 --> 01:12:50.280
So that could be that.

01:12:50.280 --> 01:12:51.170
The grandfather is older.

01:12:51.170 --> 01:12:55.050
And also, men live less
longer than women.

01:12:55.050 --> 01:13:01.960
So actually, a 65-year-old man
is quite a bit older than a

01:13:01.960 --> 01:13:03.280
60-year-old woman.

01:13:03.280 --> 01:13:05.630
So that could be a reason.

01:13:05.630 --> 01:13:08.130
So we can start looking
at this kind

01:13:08.130 --> 01:13:09.700
of stuff, for example.

01:13:09.700 --> 01:13:12.400
Also, they might want to save
more of their pension if it's

01:13:12.400 --> 01:13:15.670
a grandfather, because he's
going to die very soon.

01:13:15.670 --> 01:13:18.550
So it's more like a transitory
income shock than a permanent

01:13:18.550 --> 01:13:19.090
income shock.

01:13:19.090 --> 01:13:21.380
So you might want to
say, let's save it.

01:13:21.380 --> 01:13:23.850
So we looked at saving,
too, to control.

01:13:23.850 --> 01:13:26.370
And we couldn't find a
difference in savings.

01:13:26.370 --> 01:13:27.610
The savings seem
to be the same.

01:13:27.610 --> 01:13:34.560
But you're right, it could be
explained by that, that the

01:13:34.560 --> 01:13:36.210
grandfathers need to be
spending the money on

01:13:36.210 --> 01:13:38.408
themselves, where the
grandmother doesn't need to.

01:13:38.408 --> 01:13:41.645
AUDIENCE: Also, could it
potentially be the case that

01:13:41.645 --> 01:13:45.380
the grandmothers may be alone
in the household, with their

01:13:45.380 --> 01:13:48.119
grandchildren, therefore they
would not have to spend

01:13:48.119 --> 01:13:50.360
anything on other people.

01:13:50.360 --> 01:13:52.850
Whereas, maybe in the culture,
it's more likely that a

01:13:52.850 --> 01:13:56.114
grandfather has to take care,
also, of his wife, therefore

01:13:56.114 --> 01:13:59.036
when he becomes eligible, there
is a greater fraction of

01:13:59.036 --> 01:14:01.471
his income that also
goes to a wife.

01:14:01.471 --> 01:14:02.445
PROFESSOR: That's
a good question.

01:14:02.445 --> 01:14:03.730
That can be tested.

01:14:03.730 --> 01:14:06.080
Because you can look at
all of the family size

01:14:06.080 --> 01:14:07.360
configurations.

01:14:07.360 --> 01:14:12.060
And you seem to find these
difference regardless of who

01:14:12.060 --> 01:14:12.840
is who is who.

01:14:12.840 --> 01:14:16.400
What is interesting, which helps
answering your question,

01:14:16.400 --> 01:14:20.230
is the grandmother could be the
mother's mother or could

01:14:20.230 --> 01:14:22.460
be the father's mother.

01:14:22.460 --> 01:14:26.000
So you can look at, the pension
goes to the mother's

01:14:26.000 --> 01:14:29.670
mother or to mother's father
or to father's mother or to

01:14:29.670 --> 01:14:30.920
the father's father.

01:14:33.900 --> 01:14:36.280
Which one do you
think matters?

01:14:36.280 --> 01:14:39.920
Under your hypothesis, if it's
only due to the health issue,

01:14:39.920 --> 01:14:42.930
what should we see?

01:14:42.930 --> 01:14:45.780
That mother's mothers and
mother's fathers should be the

01:14:45.780 --> 01:14:48.960
same and then the father would
be lower, because they need

01:14:48.960 --> 01:14:50.600
more money.

01:14:50.600 --> 01:14:52.800
And then, in practice,
what do we see?

01:14:52.800 --> 01:14:57.020
These high bar is only their
mother's mother.

01:14:57.020 --> 01:15:00.250
So it's only the pension
translating to higher health

01:15:00.250 --> 01:15:04.310
of the kids if it's a maternal
grandmother of a girl.

01:15:04.310 --> 01:15:06.960
So that seemed to have something
to do with these

01:15:06.960 --> 01:15:08.830
gender lines.

01:15:08.830 --> 01:15:11.130
And that doesn't mean that the
grandmother doesn't do other

01:15:11.130 --> 01:15:12.210
things for the kids.

01:15:12.210 --> 01:15:16.220
But in terms of how they decide
to feed the kids, it's

01:15:16.220 --> 01:15:20.040
really the identity of the
kid that matters a lot.

01:15:20.040 --> 01:15:28.750
So let me show you one last
thing, which is these results

01:15:28.750 --> 01:15:32.330
seem to show, relatively
clearly, that the family is

01:15:32.330 --> 01:15:33.470
not unitary.

01:15:33.470 --> 01:15:37.880
So who brings in the
resources matters.

01:15:37.880 --> 01:15:40.310
They actually do not show that
women are better people than

01:15:40.310 --> 01:15:41.940
men, because we don't
know what men do.

01:15:41.940 --> 01:15:44.920
Maybe they spend more on the
education of the children.

01:15:44.920 --> 01:15:46.756
I only showed you
a very partial

01:15:46.756 --> 01:15:49.330
window into the family.

01:15:49.330 --> 01:15:51.940
So the only conclusion we can
take from this is that

01:15:51.940 --> 01:15:53.470
families are not unitary.

01:15:53.470 --> 01:15:55.220
So the next question we
might want to ask

01:15:55.220 --> 01:15:56.950
is, are they efficient?

01:15:56.950 --> 01:16:01.170
In that, they are bargaining
with each other, but are they

01:16:01.170 --> 01:16:03.790
bargaining in a way that they
are first maximizing the size

01:16:03.790 --> 01:16:07.650
of the pie and then deciding
to split the pie?

01:16:07.650 --> 01:16:11.640
Or are they bargaining in a way
that the women would be

01:16:11.640 --> 01:16:15.230
willing to reduce the pie as
long as she could get a higher

01:16:15.230 --> 01:16:16.110
share of it?

01:16:16.110 --> 01:16:18.230
You understand the difference?

01:16:18.230 --> 01:16:20.950
So two people who would just
meet and who don't know each

01:16:20.950 --> 01:16:23.860
other, will tend to interact
with each other like in the

01:16:23.860 --> 01:16:26.020
prisoner's dilemma, that you
might have seen in game

01:16:26.020 --> 01:16:29.420
theory, which is they will try
to grab as much of the pie as

01:16:29.420 --> 01:16:32.730
they can, even if it makes
the pie lower.

01:16:32.730 --> 01:16:36.350
But two people who know each
other very well, who are in it

01:16:36.350 --> 01:16:38.850
for the longer run, might decide
that cooperating to

01:16:38.850 --> 01:16:42.020
make the size of the pie the
biggest possible is the first

01:16:42.020 --> 01:16:45.590
thing they should do and then
think about how to share it.

01:16:45.590 --> 01:16:48.870
And this is actually an idea
we can test, because

01:16:48.870 --> 01:16:51.490
households are engaged not only
in consumption but also

01:16:51.490 --> 01:16:53.710
in production.

01:16:53.710 --> 01:16:58.100
So if the direct analogy is to
first maximize the size of the

01:16:58.100 --> 01:17:02.880
pie and then decide how you're
going divide it, are they

01:17:02.880 --> 01:17:06.530
maximizing the production
that they can have.

01:17:06.530 --> 01:17:10.250
And one way to look at that is
farming, because in a lot of

01:17:10.250 --> 01:17:14.570
countries women and men grow
different plots of land.

01:17:14.570 --> 01:17:19.010
So in Burkina Faso, the study,
by Chris Udry, looking at

01:17:19.010 --> 01:17:22.600
households in which each member
is farming their own

01:17:22.600 --> 01:17:24.490
little plot.

01:17:24.490 --> 01:17:28.650
And an efficient household
should first use the inputs

01:17:28.650 --> 01:17:32.390
the most efficiently possible
and then decide on the basis

01:17:32.390 --> 01:17:36.120
of people's bargaining power
how to share the product.

01:17:39.350 --> 01:17:42.450
Once we condition for the
quality of the plot and the

01:17:42.450 --> 01:17:45.150
crop planted, we shouldn't see
that the women get fewer

01:17:45.150 --> 01:17:50.400
fertilizer or less labor or
less input or less seeds.

01:17:50.400 --> 01:17:55.330
And in fact, instead this paper
tested it and found that

01:17:55.330 --> 01:17:59.380
women get significantly less
of every input, including

01:17:59.380 --> 01:18:00.540
fertilizer.

01:18:00.540 --> 01:18:03.190
And fertilizer has very
concave returns.

01:18:03.190 --> 01:18:06.200
So there is really no point of
putting more fertilizer on a

01:18:06.200 --> 01:18:09.600
field of the men, when you could
put a little bit on the

01:18:09.600 --> 01:18:12.520
field of a woman, from the
point of view of family

01:18:12.520 --> 01:18:13.540
production.

01:18:13.540 --> 01:18:14.870
And that's not what you see.

01:18:14.870 --> 01:18:17.620
You see all of the fertilizer
being spent on the men's field

01:18:17.620 --> 01:18:19.570
and very little on the
women's fields.

01:18:19.570 --> 01:18:23.520
Which suggests that the family
is not efficient, because they

01:18:23.520 --> 01:18:26.610
could become richer by just
reallocating resources among

01:18:26.610 --> 01:18:27.890
themselves.

01:18:27.890 --> 01:18:30.650
So this suggests that the
family is not only not

01:18:30.650 --> 01:18:37.410
unitary, but it is also
not fully efficient.

01:18:37.410 --> 01:18:39.850
Which leads us to this question,
what role does the

01:18:39.850 --> 01:18:41.460
family play?

01:18:41.460 --> 01:18:43.750
What is the family
inefficient?

01:18:43.750 --> 01:18:46.550
And what implications does have
to policy, which we'll

01:18:46.550 --> 01:18:50.630
take up after you become all
refreshed from the vacation.

